[0.001, "o", "\u001b]2;claude --continue -p 'What are the security risks with that approach?'\u0007\u001b]1;claude\u0007"]
[20.569, "o", "Based on the code I already reviewed, here are the key security risks:\r\n\r\n**Critical**\r\n\r\n1. **Plaintext passwords** (`src/routes/auth.ts:18`) — Passwords are stored without hashing. The TODO acknowledges this. Should use bcrypt/scrypt/argon2.\r\n\r\n2. **No input validation** — Neither `/register` nor `/login` validate that `email` and `password` exist or meet any requirements. An attacker could register with empty strings or inject unexpected types.\r\n\r\n3. **JWT secret from env with `!` assertion** (`src/routes/auth.ts:30`, `src/middleware/auth.ts:22`) — If `JWT_SECRET` is unset, `jwt.sign` will use `undefined`, and depending on the library version this could produce tokens signed with a weak/empty secret or throw at runtime.\r\n\r\n**High**\r\n\r\n4. **No rate limiting** — Login and register endpoints have no throttling, making them vulnerable to brute-force and credential-stuffing attacks.\r\n\r\n5. **In-memory user store** — Beyond being non-persistent, this means no account lockout, no audit trail, and the sto"]
[0.000, "o", "re resets on restart (users could re-register the same email with a different password).\r\n\r\n6. **No password complexity requirements** — Any string (including empty) is accepted as a password.\r\n\r\n**Medium**\r\n\r\n7. **Timing attack on login** (`src/routes/auth.ts:25`) — `Array.find` with `===` for password comparison leaks timing information. Should use a constant-time comparison after hashing.\r\n\r\n8. **Hardcoded public paths** (`src/middleware/auth.ts:6`) — The TODO notes this. Hardcoded paths are fragile — adding a new public route requires a code change, and a typo silently makes a route require auth (or worse, skips it).\r\n\r\n9. **No token revocation** — There's no blacklist or refresh-token mechanism. A compromised token is valid for the full 1-hour TTL with no way to invalidate it.\r\n\r\n10. **Generic role assignment** (`src/routes/auth.ts:30`) — Every user gets `role: 'user'` hardcoded in the JWT. If roles are meant to control access, there's no mechanism to assign different roles, and the role clai"]
[0.000, "o", "m in the token is trusted without server-side verification.\r\n\r\n**Low**\r\n\r\n11. **No HTTPS enforcement** — Bearer tokens sent over HTTP are trivially interceptable.\r\n\r\n12. **Verbose error messages** — `\"Email already registered\"` on `/register` (line 14) enables user enumeration.\r\n"]
